  "prompt": "What are the chances of finding work as a Non-EU Citizen after completing Master's Degree in Austria?",
  "response": "Finding work as a Non-EU citizen in Austria after completing a Master's degree can be challenging but possible. Here are some key points:\n\nOpportunities:\n1. Job Seeker Visa\n- After graduation, you have 6 months to search for employment\n- Allows legal stay while job hunting\n\nWork Permit Requirements:\n1. Qualified job offer\n2. Minimum salary threshold (approximately \u20ac2,700-3,000/month)\n3. Relevant skills matching job description\n4. Employer must prove no suitable EU candidate available\n\nFavorable Sectors:\n- IT/Technology\n- Engineering\n- Research\n- Healthcare\n- Digital industries\n- Advanced manufacturing\n\nAdvantages:\n- High-quality Austrian education\n- Strong local network\n- German language skills\n- Technical expertise\n\nChallenges:\n- Competitive job market\n- Language barriers\n- Strict immigration regulations\n- Work permit complexities\n\nRecommended Steps:\n- Learn German\n- Build professional network\n- Internships\n- University career services\n- Online job portals\n- LinkedIn networking\n- Specialized recruitment agencies\n\nProbability of success depends on individual qualifications, skills, language proficiency, and specific industry demand.",
